      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06 is not statistically significant because it exceeds the conventional threshold, usually set at $\\alpha = 0.05$. This means there is a 6% chance of observing your results if the null hypothesis were actually true. While that is a noticeable trend, it doesn't meet the strict standard of statistical significance, which requires you to reject the null hypothesis with a probability of less than 5%. Think of it as a near-miss in the eyes of traditional statistical testing.",
